column11: While Uber's potential IPO might be one of the largest ever, the company's present and future performance are sources of uncertainty for investors, market watchers and other interested observers (Fortune, Financial Times, Bloomberg).Outcome will be determined by the end-of-day Market Capitalization figure reported by Bloomberg.

Adjusting slightly based on expected listing tomorrow, May 10 at a price of $45/share for an implied market cap of $82.4 billion. Depending on trading activity, closing price could be higher (or lower), but I expect there will be some upward movement given pricing at the somewhat lower end of the range. It may also get a pop if investors think we are heading toward recession, given recent yield curve inversion, in the hopes of making a quick profit. The price would have to increase over 20% to exceed the $100 million mark, so I'm still only giving that a 25% chance.

The talk about this deal has become 100% weak. Pricing at the low end of the range, only 5x oversubscribed instead of 10x, pricing in a weak market...$100 billion + is now off the table. Morgan Stanley is going to have its hands full just to stabilize the price, and that stabilization is the only reason why I am closing the door on $70 billion or below.

Consensus seems to price IPO around $90b. Of course possible it will rise/decline opening day and end up higher/lower. With recent market trends and fact Uber has yet to make $, thinking people will exercise caution. But a 15% bump would take them over $100b.

Uber is shooting for a high point of about $100B according to Business Insider and other media sources. This is an optimistic figure from media speculation, and even if they are oversubscribed, they may face activities of certain investors like the ones in facebook's IPO, when the shares were sold en masse to lower the price then repurchased at the lower price point. Therefore, I think the likelihood that it will be $40-$100 is the highest probability, with the lower side being more likely. The other 15% over $100B is a short term prediction, as I think even if they do close that high, their shares will drop significantly over the next few days.

If opening price is anywhere near $100 billion, the closing price could exceed the $100 billion mark. On the other hand, Lyft's IPO "puke fest" (to quote ddorsey) indicates a weakness in the overall market for publicly traded stock on the ride hailing sector. On the third hand, it is April 1, but I doubt that Bloomberg would run an April Fool's joke about Lyft, given the likely illegality of such an act.

Going out on a limp here, but given Lyft's recent IPO I'm making the following base assumptions... 1) Lyft opened at ~38% higher than any reasonable assessment of their value, Uber will likely follow suit (SD 1/2 the delta, so 19%) 2) Lyft trended downward all day and closed down ~11%, Uber will likely do the same (same metric for SD, so 5.5%) 3) Uber's valuation prior to their IPO will remain within 5% of it's current value 4) Uber's valuation itself... I'll baseline with CrunchBase's estimate, derived from Lyft's metric of 9.1 x Net Revenue gives $109.9 billion... Holy *@#$ let's make this more reasonable... As they point out Lyft grew by 100% in 2018, Uber by "only" 43%, so let's assume 57% of the delta between their known value a year ago ($72 billion) gives an estimate of $93.6 billion

Uber's most recent valuation came in at $76 billion when Toyota announced it would invest $500 million in the company. As of Q3 2018, Uber continues showing an increase in losses as it continues to invest in future growth areas ($527 million in losses on an EBITDA basis). As it keeps expanding its operations throughout the world, monthly active riders and number of rides delivered are expected to continue growing. On its part, Eats showed a growth over 150% year over year according to the Q3 2018 financial results. A recent valuation by Wall Street bankers came in at $120 million, which surprised investors as it appears to be quite high. Thus, the valuation between $70 billion and $100 billion appears more likely. Considering that competitor firm Lyft has also announced an IPO for 2019, it seems unlikely that Uber would not have its IPO by October. Estimates for IPO price range from $70-120 billion. The question asks what the market cap will be at end of trading. I therefore took into account both opening price and first-day trading activity. Since this is the most anticipated IPO of 2019, it's going to have a lot of investor interest and likely will open above the IPO price and will trade on huge volumes the first day. Best Nasdaq IPO 1-day performers in 2018 averaged close to 100% above IPO price. I suspect the underwriters will want to be a little conservative so that some investors ca take first day profits on the hype. In addition, we should see lots of volume early on as investors try to get in, driving up the 1st day price. While a 100% increase over IPO prices seems unlikely, some of the best tech performers of 2018 saw 33% 1-day returns and they were no where near the hype Uber is getting. If the underwriters price the stock at $100 billion, it doesn't seem unreasonable for 1st-day close to be at 50% above that ($150 billion). I'm not talking about sustainable prices, I'm just talking about 1st day hype and valuation at the close. Given the current uncertainties in the overall market and signs of softening, investors might see it as a particularly appetizing IPO (irrational but not unexpected) and drive price up. This seems the most likely scenario. Given the broad valuation range, I'll stick with $100 billion for now and assume a 50% pop as most likely (60%), with 35% at $100-$130, assuming a more tepid response. There is a possibility that investors won't like Uber's performance to date and, if the market sags substantially, they could decide to wait, but given the hype I see this is only a slightly non-trivial probability (5%).

Guassian principles applied to a 74 billion mean and 44.2 billion standard deviation. Then the fact that they are aiming to get it done by 2019 made me give them 3:1 odds of doing it. They need to do it by the first 3/4 of the year so I reduced by a factor of 3:4. Then they are aiming for the second half of the year so that reduces our range again, this time by 1:3. Finally, they are have incentive to beat Lyft, so I tacked on a 7:4 odds for that piece. Multiplying these odds I got 63:48. Or 57% chance of completion.
